history.content: The topics covered in CS 172 and Math 136 are not identical. Based on the previous offerings of CS 172 by Professor Luca Trevisan, it starts with Computability Theory and transitions to complexity classes later in the semester while Math 136 does not really go into Complexity Theory. It covers Computability Theory and goes further in depth to Recursion Theory and Godel's Incompleteness theorem based on the description of the course. If you really enjoy the P vs NP portion of 170, I would suggest you take CS 172 since complexity theory may not be covered at all in Math 136. Plus Professor Alistair Sinclair is amazing!

children.subject: Thanks for the reply! Might enroll in each and see which one is more fun, or do both!

history.content:
I'm looking to take one of these classes next semester since they're both being offered next semester but I don't think I should do both because I think they overlap a lot. I was wondering if people can comment on what the classes were like- specifically 172 since it is rarely offered.

Right now I'm leaning to 136 because it seems as though it would incorprate more mathematical logic whereas 172 will have more complexity, and I found 170 to be quite hard. However, I did enjoy the P vs NP portion of 170
